{"title":"Check folder size in Bash","commands":["du -h your_directory \u0026\u0026 ","du -hs /path/to/directory \u0026\u0026 --apparent-size\n      print  apparent  sizes,  rather  than  disk  usage; although the apparent size is usually smaller, it may be larger due to holes in (\u0027sparse\u0027)\n      files, internal fragmentation, indirect blocks, and the like \u0026\u0026 -b, --bytes\n      equivalent to \u0027--apparent-size --block-size\u003d1\u0027 \u0026\u0026 #!/bin/bash\nSIZE\u003d$(du -B 1 /path/to/directory | cut -f 1 -d \"   \")    \n# 2GB \u003d 2147483648 bytes\n# 10GB \u003d 10737418240 bytes\nif [[ $SIZE -gt 2147483648 \u0026\u0026 $SIZE -lt 10737418240 ]]; then\n    echo \u0027Condition returned True\u0027\nfi \u0026\u0026 ","CHECK\u003d$(du -sb /data/sflow_log | cut -f1) \u0026\u0026 ","du --max-depth\u003d0 ./directory \u0026\u0026 5234232       ./directory \u0026\u0026 ","$du -s --block-size\u003dM /path/to/your/directory/ \u0026\u0026 "]}